## Round 202604280500 forward-looking entries

Audit-driven follow-up chain Round B. Storage-side of the Sign axis +
bit-width cap to 256 lands; arithmetic and a few cross-strategy
extensions defer to follow-up rounds:

- **UFixed / IFixed at 129..=256 logical width.** Awaits UArith /
  IArith dispatch on `MultiContainer<HiT, LoT>` (multi-precision add
  with carry, multi-precision mul with double-width intermediate,
  saturating variants on Precise). Round B-arith / Round C follow-up.
  Bits at those widths is available standalone; UFixed / IFixed cap
  at 128 in this round and surface a `UArith` /  `IArith` unimplemented
  diagnostic at 129..=256 pointing at the BACKLOG entry.
- **UWidenFrom / UNarrowFrom for MultiContainer.** Cross-strategy and
  cross-container widening / narrowing through `MultiContainer<HiT,
  LoT>` shapes. Required before Bits<M, S, Sign> → Bits<N, S, Sign>
  conversions work transparently across the 1..=256 range. Round
  B-arith follow-up.
- **Warm / Precise extension to 65..=256.** The 2x-logical safety
  contract for Warm (and the same shape adopted by Precise with
  saturating arithmetic) collapses without a 256-bit native primitive.
  Two design paths: (a) define Warm at 65..=256 as
  `MultiContainer<u128, u128>` and accept the contract loss as a
  BACKLOG-warned diagnostic, (b) keep Warm capped at 64 / 128 with a
  diagnostic pointing at Hot. Round B opted for (b) pending a
  considered design call. Future round resolves.
- **u128-native cells in Hot 65..=128 range.** The current dispatch
  uses native `u128` for Hot 65..=128. A bench-driven follow-up may
  reroute some cells (e.g. 121..=128 where `MultiContainer<u64, u64>`
  matches u128 storage but allows consumer-controlled half access)
  through MultiContainer instead. BACKLOG-tracked; bench evidence
  drives the call per the always-optimal-internals rule.
- **Sign axis on `Mask<W>` and other bit-level traits.** Round B
  introduces the Sign axis on Bits only. Mask<W> / BitLogic /
  BitAccess / BitSequence stay sign-agnostic in this round (the
  trait surface acts on raw bit patterns, which is sign-agnostic by
  construction). If a consumer surfaces a need for sign-aware bit
  ops, a future round adds it.

